1
00:00:01,084 --> 00:00:03,003
(WHOOSHING)

2
00:00:07,299 --> 00:00:08,926
-DOCTOR: Cardiff!
-Cardiff?

3
00:00:09,051 --> 00:00:12,804
Ah, but the thing about Cardiff,
it's built on a rift in time and space.

4
00:00:12,888 --> 00:00:16,350
Just like California on the San Andreas
Fault, but the rift bleeds energy.

5
00:00:16,433 --> 00:00:19,394
Every now and then I need to open up
the engines, soak up the energy,

6
00:00:19,478 --> 00:00:21,730
-and use it as fuel.
-So it's a pit stop?

7
00:00:21,813 --> 00:00:26,443
Exactly! Should only take 20 seconds.
The rift's been active.

8
00:00:29,613 --> 00:00:32,866
Wait a minute. They had an earthquake
in Cardiff a couple of years ago.

9
00:00:32,950 --> 00:00:35,494
-Was that you?
-Bit of trouble with the Slitheen.

10
00:00:38,622 --> 00:00:43,460
A long time ago. Lifetimes.
I was a different man back then.

11
00:00:44,753 --> 00:00:47,965
Doctor!

12
00:00:48,632 --> 00:00:51,093
Finito. All powered up.

13
00:01:06,775 --> 00:01:08,735
What's that?

14
00:01:11,989 --> 00:01:16,827
We're accelerating into the future.
The year one billion. Five billion.

15
00:01:16,910 --> 00:01:19,788
Five trillion. Fifty trillion? What?

16
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:22,416
The year 100 trillion?
That's impossible.

17
00:01:22,499 --> 00:01:24,501
Why? What happens then?

18
00:01:26,628 --> 00:01:29,298
We're going to the end of the universe.

19
00:01:29,381 --> 00:01:32,593
Doctor!

20
00:01:41,351 --> 00:01:45,188
Humans. Humans are coming.

21
00:01:47,357 --> 00:01:50,027
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

22
00:02:34,488 --> 00:02:37,282
I just want to go. Please let me go.

23
00:02:37,824 --> 00:02:40,077
Human!

24
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:42,412
Human!

25
00:02:45,374 --> 00:02:50,420
-Human!
-Human!

26
00:02:50,754 --> 00:02:52,464
A hunt!

27
00:02:55,133 --> 00:02:56,551
Hunt!

28
00:02:57,094 --> 00:02:59,262
(ALL CHANTING)

29
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:01,473
Hunt. Hunt.

30
00:03:01,932 --> 00:03:03,767
(BEEPING)

31
00:03:06,561 --> 00:03:11,817
There's movement on the surface.
Another human hunt. God help him.

32
00:03:11,942 --> 00:03:13,902
Chan, should I alert the guards, tho?

33
00:03:13,985 --> 00:03:17,739
No, no, we can't spare them.
Poor beggar's on his own.

34
00:03:17,823 --> 00:03:21,451
One more lost soul dreaming of Utopia.

35
00:03:21,576 --> 00:03:24,246
Chan, you mustn't talk as though
you've given up, tho.

36
00:03:24,329 --> 00:03:28,291
No, no, indeed. Here's to it. Utopia.

37
00:03:30,627 --> 00:03:35,173
Well, it is to be hoped the coffee
is a little less sour. Will you join me?

38
00:03:35,257 --> 00:03:38,468
Chan, I am happy drinking
my own internal milk, tho.

39
00:03:38,593 --> 00:03:41,596
Yes, well. That's quite enough
information, thank you.

40
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:45,600
OVER PA: Professor Yana. Don't want
to rush you, but how are we doing?

41
00:03:45,684 --> 00:03:49,563
(STUTTERING) Yes, yes, working.
Yes, almost there.

42
00:03:49,646 --> 00:03:52,190
How's it looking on the Footprint?

43
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:56,069
It's good. Yes, fine, excellent.

44
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,451
Chan, there's no problem as such.

45
00:04:02,534 --> 00:04:04,870
We've accelerated
the calculation matrix,

46
00:04:04,995 --> 00:04:07,831
but it's going to take time
to harmonise, tho.

47
00:04:07,956 --> 00:04:10,333
Chan, we're trying
a new reversal process.

48
00:04:10,459 --> 00:04:14,004
We'll have a definite result
in approximately two hours, tho.

49
00:04:14,212 --> 00:04:16,131
(DRUMS BEATING)

50
00:04:16,631 --> 00:04:19,092
(DISTANT) Chan, Professor, tho?

51
00:04:21,553 --> 00:04:23,680
Chan, Professor Yana, tho?

52
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:26,767
Chan, Professor, tho.

53
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:30,020
Yes, yes, yes, working.

54
00:04:30,479 --> 00:04:32,773
Chan, it's the surface scanner,
Professor.

55
00:04:32,856 --> 00:04:36,193
It seems to be detecting
a different signal, tho.

56
00:04:37,360 --> 00:04:42,407
Well, that's not a standard reading.
I can't make it out.

57
00:04:43,408 --> 00:04:46,870
It would seem something new has arrived.

58
00:04:51,374 --> 00:04:53,919
Well, we've landed.

59
00:04:54,169 --> 00:04:57,088
-So what's out there?
-I don't know.

60
00:04:58,048 --> 00:05:02,427
-Say that again. That's rare.
-Not even the Time Lords came this far.

61
00:05:03,011 --> 00:05:06,139
We should leave. We should go.

62
00:05:06,223 --> 00:05:10,852
We should really, really go.

63
00:05:27,619 --> 00:05:29,538
Oh, my God.

64
00:05:30,914 --> 00:05:35,418
Can't get a pulse. Hold on,
you've got that medical kit thing.

65
00:05:37,254 --> 00:05:41,383
Hello again. Oh, I'm sorry.

66
00:05:42,509 --> 00:05:44,886
Here we go. Get out of the way.

67
00:05:44,970 --> 00:05:46,763
It's a bit odd, though,
not very 100 trillion.

68
00:05:46,847 --> 00:05:48,390
That coat's more like World War II.

69
00:05:48,473 --> 00:05:51,017
-I think he came with us.
-How do you mean? From Earth?

70
00:05:51,101 --> 00:05:54,312
Must've been clinging
to the outside of the Tardis.

71
00:05:54,396 --> 00:05:56,940
All the way through the vortex.
Well, that's very him.

72
00:05:57,065 --> 00:05:59,192
-What, do you know him?
-Friend of mine.

73
00:05:59,276 --> 00:06:02,529
Used to travel with me.
Back in the old days.

74
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:08,535
But he's... I'm sorry, there's no
heartbeat. There's nothing. He's dead.

75
00:06:11,121 --> 00:06:15,041
Oh, so much for me. It's all right,
just breathe deep. I've got you.

76
00:06:16,001 --> 00:06:19,588
Captain Jack Harkness. And who are you?

77
00:06:19,671 --> 00:06:22,090
-Martha Jones.
-Nice to meet you, Martha Jones.

78
00:06:22,173 --> 00:06:25,510
-Oh, don't start.
-I was only saying hello.

79
00:06:25,635 --> 00:06:27,095
I don't mind.

80
00:06:33,310 --> 00:06:34,978
-Doctor.
-Captain.

81
00:06:36,605 --> 00:06:38,899
-Good to see you.
-And you.

82
00:06:38,982 --> 00:06:42,652
Same as ever.
Although, have you had work done?

83
00:06:42,777 --> 00:06:47,032
-You can talk.
-Oh, yes, the face. Regeneration.

84
00:06:47,157 --> 00:06:50,201
-How did you know this was me?
-The police box kind of gives it away.

85
00:06:50,327 --> 00:06:55,123
I've been following you
for a long time. You abandoned me.

86
00:06:55,206 --> 00:06:58,835
Did I? Busy life. Moving on.

87
00:06:58,919 --> 00:07:01,880
Just got to ask.
The Battle of Canary Wharf.

88
00:07:01,963 --> 00:07:05,967
I saw the list of the dead.
It said Rose Tyler.

89
00:07:06,051 --> 00:07:09,054
-Oh, no, sorry. She's alive.
-You're kidding!

90
00:07:09,179 --> 00:07:12,223
Parallel world, safe and sound.
And Mickey. And her mother.

91
00:07:12,349 --> 00:07:13,642
Oh, yes!

92
00:07:17,687 --> 00:07:18,855
Good old Rose.

93
00:07:26,237 --> 00:07:28,865
So there I was,
stranded in the year 200100,

94
00:07:28,949 --> 00:07:32,911
ankle-deep in Dalek dust, and he goes
off without me, but I had this.

95
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:36,039
I used to be a Time Agent.
It's called a vortex manipulator.

96
00:07:36,122 --> 00:07:38,041
He's not the only one
who can time travel.

97
00:07:38,166 --> 00:07:40,585
Excuse me, that is not time travel.

98
00:07:40,710 --> 00:07:43,797
It's like, I've got a sports car,
you've got a space hopper.

99
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:48,259
-Oh, boys and their toys!
-All right, so I bounced.

100
00:07:48,343 --> 00:07:51,429
I thought, "21st century,
the best place to find the Doctor.”

101
00:07:51,554 --> 00:07:55,183
Except I got it a little wrong,
arrived in 1869,

102
00:07:55,266 --> 00:07:57,227
this thing burnt out, so it was useless.

103
00:07:57,310 --> 00:07:58,770
Told you.

104
00:07:58,895 --> 00:08:00,939
I had to live through
the entire 20th century

105
00:08:01,064 --> 00:08:03,692
waiting for a version of you
that would coincide with me.

106
00:08:03,775 --> 00:08:05,610
But that makes you
more than 100 years old.

107
00:08:05,694 --> 00:08:08,613
And looking good, don't you think?

108
00:08:08,697 --> 00:08:11,908
So, I went to the time rift,
based myself there,

109
00:08:11,992 --> 00:08:15,453
'cause I knew you'd come back
to refuel, until finally,

110
00:08:15,578 --> 00:08:17,998
I get a signal on this detecting you
and here we are.

111
00:08:18,081 --> 00:08:20,000
But the thing is,
how come you left him behind, Doctor?

112
00:08:20,083 --> 00:08:21,251
I was busy.

113
00:08:21,376 --> 00:08:23,336
Is that what happens, though, seriously?

114
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:25,463
Do you just get bored of us
one day and disappear?

115
00:08:25,588 --> 00:08:28,967
-Not if you're blonde.
-Oh, she was blonde! What a surprise!

116
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:32,012
You two,
we're at the end of the universe, right?

117
00:08:32,095 --> 00:08:36,433
Right at the edge of knowledge itself
and you're busy...

118
00:08:36,516 --> 00:08:38,101
blogging!

119
00:08:38,810 --> 00:08:40,311
Come on.

120
00:08:48,111 --> 00:08:49,237
Is that a city?

121
00:08:49,320 --> 00:08:53,533
City or a hive or a nest.
Or a conglomeration.

122
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:58,121
Like it was grown.
But look, there, that's like

123
00:08:58,204 --> 00:09:00,457
pathways or roads.

124
00:09:01,458 --> 00:09:04,044
There must've been some sort of life.

125
00:09:04,127 --> 00:09:07,130
-Long ago.
-What killed it?

126
00:09:08,214 --> 00:09:13,595
Time. Just time. Everything's dying now.
All the great civilisations have gone.

127
00:09:14,679 --> 00:09:19,976
This isn't just night. All the stars
have burnt up and faded away

128
00:09:21,394 --> 00:09:23,146
into nothing.

129
00:09:23,271 --> 00:09:27,901
They must have an atmospheric shell.
We should be frozen to death.

130
00:09:28,526 --> 00:09:34,157
Well, Martha and I, maybe.
Not so sure about you, Jack.

131
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:39,788
But what about the people?
Does no one survive?

132
00:09:40,705 --> 00:09:46,002
I suppose we have to hope
life will find a way.

133
00:09:47,754 --> 00:09:50,006
Well, he's not doing too bad.

134
00:09:52,008 --> 00:09:53,676
(ALL YELLING)

135
00:09:54,302 --> 00:09:57,430
Is it me or does that look like a hunt?
Come on!

136
00:10:03,978 --> 00:10:05,855
Oh, I've missed this!

137
00:10:20,870 --> 00:10:24,374
-I've got you. I've got you...
-We've got to run. They're coming!

138
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:28,086
Jack, don't you dare!

139
00:10:32,090 --> 00:10:33,550
What the hell are they?

140
00:10:33,633 --> 00:10:35,260
There's more of them.
We've got to keep going.

141
00:10:35,385 --> 00:10:39,180
I've got a ship nearby. It's safe.
It's not far. It's over there.

142
00:10:39,264 --> 00:10:41,558
-Or maybe not.
-We're close to the silo.

143
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:44,060
-If we get to the silo, then we're safe.
-Silo?

144
00:10:44,185 --> 00:10:45,937
-Silo.
-Silo for me.

145
00:10:56,072 --> 00:10:58,992
It's the Futurekind, they're coming!
Open the gate!

146
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:01,035
Show me your teeth!

147
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:07,292
Show me your teeth! Show me your teeth!

148
00:11:07,375 --> 00:11:09,419
Show him your teeth!

149
00:11:12,338 --> 00:11:15,425
Human! Let them in! Let them in!

150
00:11:15,967 --> 00:11:18,094
-Close!
-Close!

151
00:11:18,178 --> 00:11:19,929
Close!

152
00:11:28,938 --> 00:11:32,984
Humans. Humani.

153
00:11:34,944 --> 00:11:38,281
-Make feast.
-Go back to where you came from.

154
00:11:39,282 --> 00:11:42,243
I said go back! Back!

155
00:11:42,327 --> 00:11:44,829
-Oh, don't tell him to put his gun down.
-He's not my responsibility.

156
00:11:44,954 --> 00:11:47,081
And I am? That makes a change.

157
00:11:47,165 --> 00:11:48,875
Kind want you.

158
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:52,128
(GRUNTS)

159
00:11:52,253 --> 00:11:54,130
Kind hungry.

160
00:11:56,674 --> 00:11:58,134
(SHOUTS)

161
00:12:07,310 --> 00:12:10,396
-Thanks for that.
-Right, let's get you inside.

162
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:15,693
My name is Padra Fet Shafe Cane.
Tell me, just tell me.

163
00:12:15,777 --> 00:12:20,156
-Can you take me to Utopia?
-Oh, yes, sir. Yes, I can.

164
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:27,789
Professor,
we've got four new humans inside.

165
00:12:27,872 --> 00:12:30,416
One of them is calling himself a doctor.

166
00:12:30,541 --> 00:12:33,461
-Of medicine?
-He says of everything.

167
00:12:33,544 --> 00:12:37,048
What? A scientist! Oh, my word!

168
00:12:37,131 --> 00:12:42,345
(STUTTERING) Chantho, just...
I don't know. I'm coming!

169
00:12:46,099 --> 00:12:48,101
DOCTOR: It's like a box, a big blue box.

170
00:12:48,184 --> 00:12:51,229
I'm sorry, but I really need it back.
It's stuck out there.

171
00:12:51,354 --> 00:12:55,024
I'm sorry, but my family were heading
for the silo. Did they get here?

172
00:12:55,108 --> 00:12:58,278
My mother is Kistane Shafe Cane.
My brother's name is Beltone.

173
00:12:58,361 --> 00:13:01,030
Computers are down, but you can
check the paperwork. Creet!

174
00:13:01,155 --> 00:13:04,033
-Passenger needs help.
-Right, what do you need?

175
00:13:05,201 --> 00:13:07,620
A blue box, you said?

176
00:13:07,704 --> 00:13:11,082
Big, tall, wooden, says "Police".

177
00:13:11,165 --> 00:13:14,127
We're driving out for the last water
collection. I'll see what I can do.

178
00:13:14,210 --> 00:13:15,878
Thank you.

179
00:13:15,962 --> 00:13:18,256
Come on.

180
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:22,760
-Sorry, but how old are you?
-Old enough to work. This way.

181
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:28,516
CREET: Kistane Shafe Cane.

182
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:32,645
Kistane and Beltone Shafe Cane.

183
00:13:32,729 --> 00:13:35,064
I'm looking for a Kistane
and Beltone Shafe Cane.

184
00:13:35,189 --> 00:13:38,318
PADRA: The Shafe Canes, anyone?
CREET: Anyone?

185
00:13:38,943 --> 00:13:41,946
Kistane and Beltone Shafe Cane.

186
00:13:42,071 --> 00:13:45,783
Anyone know the Shafe Cane family?
Anyone called Shafe Cane?

187
00:13:47,744 --> 00:13:50,455
It's like a refugee camp.

188
00:13:50,538 --> 00:13:54,500
It's stinking.
Sorry. No offence. Not you.

189
00:13:54,584 --> 00:13:58,504
Don't you see, though? The ripe old
smell of humans. You survived.

190
00:13:58,588 --> 00:14:02,425
Oh, you might've spent a million years
evolving into clouds of gas

191
00:14:02,592 --> 00:14:04,093
and another million as downloads,

192
00:14:04,218 --> 00:14:07,263
but you always revert
to the same basic shape.

193
00:14:07,388 --> 00:14:08,931
The fundamental human.

194
00:14:09,098 --> 00:14:10,433
CREET: Kistane Shafe Cane.

195
00:14:10,516 --> 00:14:14,270
End of the universe and here you are.
Indomitable, that's the word!

196
00:14:14,354 --> 00:14:16,105
Indomitable!

197
00:14:16,939 --> 00:14:19,192
Is there a Kistane Shafe Cane?

198
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:21,569
-That's me.
-Mother!

199
00:14:21,652 --> 00:14:24,197
KISTANE: Oh, my God. Padra!

200
00:14:24,781 --> 00:14:26,699
It's not all bad news.

201
00:14:29,619 --> 00:14:35,792
-Captain Jack Harkness. And who are you?
-Stop it. Give us a hand with this.

202
00:14:38,586 --> 00:14:41,047
It's half-deadlocked.
See if you can overwrite the code.

203
00:14:41,130 --> 00:14:43,383
Let's find out where we are.

204
00:14:46,719 --> 00:14:49,055
JACK: I've got you.
DOCTOR: Thanks.

205
00:14:49,138 --> 00:14:51,224
How did you cope without me?

206
00:14:51,307 --> 00:14:54,519
Now that is what I call a rocket.

207
00:14:54,644 --> 00:14:56,771
DOCTOR: They're not refugees,
they're passengers.

208
00:14:57,230 --> 00:14:58,981
He said they were going to Utopia.

209
00:14:59,065 --> 00:15:02,944
The perfect place. 100 trillion years
and it's the same old dream.

210
00:15:03,027 --> 00:15:04,821
DOCTOR: Do you recognise those engines?

211
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:09,992
Nope, whatever it is, it's not rocket
science. But it's hot, though.

212
00:15:10,118 --> 00:15:11,494
Boiling.

213
00:15:14,372 --> 00:15:18,292
But if the universe is falling apart,
what does Utopia mean?

214
00:15:20,002 --> 00:15:21,963
-The Doctor?
-That's me.

215
00:15:22,046 --> 00:15:24,674
Good! Good! Good!

216
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:28,678
Good, good, good. Good!

217
00:15:28,761 --> 00:15:30,930
It's good, apparently.

218
00:15:35,059 --> 00:15:36,727
Chan, welcome, tho.

219
00:15:36,853 --> 00:15:40,690
This is the gravitissimal accelerator.
It's past its best,

220
00:15:40,773 --> 00:15:42,817
-but it works.
-Chan, welcome, tho.

221
00:15:42,900 --> 00:15:45,570
And over here is
the Footprint Impeller System.

222
00:15:45,653 --> 00:15:47,530
Do you know anything
about end-time gravity mechanics?

223
00:15:47,697 --> 00:15:50,825
-Hello. Who are you?
-Chan, Chantho, tho.

224
00:15:51,409 --> 00:15:53,369
But we can't get it to harmonise.

225
00:15:53,453 --> 00:15:55,413
-Captain Jack Harkness.
-Stop it.

226
00:15:55,496 --> 00:15:59,292
-Can't I say hello to anyone?
-Chan, I do not protest, tho.

227
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:02,795
Maybe later, blue.
So what have we got here?

228
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:07,717
-And all this feeds into the rocket?
-Yes, except without a stable Footprint,

229
00:16:07,842 --> 00:16:10,219
we'll never achieve escape velocity.

230
00:16:10,344 --> 00:16:13,473
If only we could harmonise
the five impact patterns

231
00:16:13,556 --> 00:16:16,893
and unify them,
well, we might yet make it.

232
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:21,147
What do you think, Doctor? Any ideas?

233
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:26,360
Well, basically, sort of, not a clue.

234
00:16:27,361 --> 00:16:28,571
Nothing?

235
00:16:28,654 --> 00:16:31,949
I'm not from round these parts.
I've never seen a system like it.

236
00:16:32,033 --> 00:16:35,119
-Sorry.
-No, no, I'm sorry. It's my fault.

237
00:16:35,203 --> 00:16:36,871
There's been so little help...

238
00:16:36,954 --> 00:16:39,332
Oh, my God.

239
00:16:41,334 --> 00:16:43,461
You've got a hand.

240
00:16:43,544 --> 00:16:47,256
A hand in a jar.
A hand, in a jar, in your bag.

241
00:16:47,340 --> 00:16:49,884
(STUTTERING) That's my hand.

242
00:16:49,967 --> 00:16:51,844
I said I had a Doctor detector.

243
00:16:51,928 --> 00:16:54,722
Chan, is this is a tradition
amongst your people, tho?

244
00:16:54,805 --> 00:16:56,474
Not on my street!
What do you mean, that's your hand?

245
00:16:56,557 --> 00:16:58,184
You've got both your hands,
I can see them.

246
00:16:58,267 --> 00:17:01,521
Long story. I lost my hand,
Christmas Day in a sword fight.

247
00:17:07,735 --> 00:17:10,154
What, and you grew another hand?

248
00:17:10,238 --> 00:17:13,699
Yeah, yeah I did, yeah. Hello.

249
00:17:13,783 --> 00:17:17,078
Might I ask, what species are you?

250
00:17:17,703 --> 00:17:22,875
Time Lord. Last of.
Heard of them? Legend or anything?

251
00:17:24,627 --> 00:17:27,630
Not even a myth? Blimey,
end of the universe is a bit humbling.

252
00:17:27,755 --> 00:17:31,467
Chan, it is said that I am
the last of my species too, tho.

253
00:17:31,551 --> 00:17:35,179
-Sorry. What was your name?
-My assistant and good friend, Chantho.

254
00:17:35,304 --> 00:17:38,683
A survivor of the Malmooth.
This was their planet, Malcassairo,

255
00:17:38,766 --> 00:17:40,643
before we took refuge.

256
00:17:40,768 --> 00:17:45,356
-The city outside. That was yours?
-Chan, the conglomeration died, tho.

257
00:17:45,439 --> 00:17:47,441
Conglomeration! That's what I said!

258
00:17:47,525 --> 00:17:50,278
-You're supposed to say sorry.
-Oh, yes.

259
00:17:50,861 --> 00:17:53,948
-Sorry.
-Chan, most grateful, tho.

260
00:17:54,031 --> 00:17:56,909
You grew another hand?

261
00:17:56,993 --> 00:18:01,622
Hello again. It's fine.
Look, really, it's me.

262
00:18:04,542 --> 00:18:08,004
All this time
and you're still full of surprises.

263
00:18:08,254 --> 00:18:11,007
-Chan, you are most unusual, tho.
-Well...

264
00:18:11,549 --> 00:18:14,302
So what about those things outside,
the Beastie Boys? What are they?

265
00:18:14,385 --> 00:18:18,055
We call them the Futurekind,
which is a myth in itself,

266
00:18:18,139 --> 00:18:22,435
but it's feared
they are what we will become.

267
00:18:22,518 --> 00:18:26,981
-Unless we reach Utopia.
-And Utopia is...?

268
00:18:27,064 --> 00:18:30,818
Every human knows of Utopia.
Where have you been?

269
00:18:30,901 --> 00:18:32,695
Bit of a hermit.

270
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:37,116
-A hermit with friends?
-Hermits United.

271
00:18:37,199 --> 00:18:40,870
We meet up every 10 years, swap
stories about caves. It's good fun.

272
00:18:40,953 --> 00:18:44,248
For a hermit. So, Utopia?

273
00:18:49,920 --> 00:18:54,675
The call came from across the stars.
Over and over again.

274
00:18:54,967 --> 00:18:58,095
"Come to Utopia."”
Originating from that point.

275
00:18:58,179 --> 00:18:59,347
Where is that?

276
00:18:59,430 --> 00:19:02,224
Oh, it's far beyond
the Condensate Wilderness.

277
00:19:02,350 --> 00:19:05,728
Out towards the Wildlands
and the Dark Matter Reefs.

278
00:19:05,895 --> 00:19:07,605
Calling us in,

279
00:19:07,688 --> 00:19:11,567
the last of the humans
scattered across the night.

280
00:19:11,651 --> 00:19:14,153
DOCTOR: What do you think is out there?
YANA: We can't know.

281
00:19:14,236 --> 00:19:17,907
A colony, a city, some sort of haven.

282
00:19:17,990 --> 00:19:22,078
The Science Foundation created the
Utopia Project thousands of years ago

283
00:19:22,161 --> 00:19:26,082
to preserve mankind,
to find a way of surviving

284
00:19:26,165 --> 00:19:29,168
beyond the collapse of reality itself.

285
00:19:29,251 --> 00:19:31,462
Now, perhaps they found it.

286
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:35,591
Perhaps not.
But it's worth a look, don't you think?

287
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:37,343
Oh, yes.

288
00:19:37,426 --> 00:19:38,803
(DRUMS BEATING)

289
00:19:38,886 --> 00:19:41,847
And the signal keeps modulating
so it's not on automatic.

290
00:19:41,931 --> 00:19:44,934
That's a good sign. Someone's out there.

291
00:19:45,017 --> 00:19:48,521
(DISTANT) And that's
a navigation matrix, isn't it?

292
00:19:48,604 --> 00:19:52,483
So you can fly without the stars
to guide you, Professor?

293
00:19:53,317 --> 00:19:56,028
Professor? Professor?

294
00:19:57,279 --> 00:19:58,989
Professor!

295
00:19:59,073 --> 00:20:02,201
I... Right, that's enough talk.
There's work to do.

296
00:20:02,284 --> 00:20:04,829
Now if you could leave, thank you.

297
00:20:05,371 --> 00:20:08,916
-Are you all right?
-Yes, I'm fine. And busy.

298
00:20:09,792 --> 00:20:13,713
Except that rocket's
not going to fly, is it?

299
00:20:14,463 --> 00:20:18,801
This Footprint mechanism thing,
it's not working.

300
00:20:19,635 --> 00:20:23,305
-We'll find a way!
-You're stuck on this planet.

301
00:20:24,473 --> 00:20:27,143
And you haven't told them, have you?

302
00:20:27,226 --> 00:20:30,563
That lot out there,
they still think they're gonna fly.

303
00:20:30,646 --> 00:20:33,023
Well, it's better
to let them live in hope.

304
00:20:33,107 --> 00:20:38,696
Quite right, too. And I must say,
Professor... What was it?

305
00:20:38,821 --> 00:20:40,197
-Yana.
-Professor Yana,

306
00:20:40,322 --> 00:20:42,366
this new science is well beyond me.

307
00:20:42,450 --> 00:20:45,161
But all the same, a boost
reversal circuit, in any time frame,

308
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:47,955
must be a circuit
which reverses the boost.

309
00:20:48,038 --> 00:20:50,916
So I wonder what would happen

310
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:54,420
if I did...this.

311
00:20:56,797 --> 00:20:59,175
Chan, it's working, tho!

312
00:20:59,258 --> 00:21:02,011
But how did you do that?

313
00:21:02,595 --> 00:21:06,515
Oh, we've been chatting away.
I forgot to tell you, I'm brilliant.

314
00:21:09,018 --> 00:21:11,061
All passengers, prepare for boarding.

315
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:14,523
Repeat, all passengers
prepare for immediate boarding.

316
00:21:26,869 --> 00:21:29,205
Destination, Utopia.

317
00:21:32,917 --> 00:21:34,752
In there.

318
00:21:50,267 --> 00:21:54,146
Inside! Everyone, inside!

319
00:21:55,231 --> 00:21:57,441
Come on, move, move, move!

320
00:22:04,406 --> 00:22:07,868
All passengers
prepare for immediate boarding.

321
00:22:08,327 --> 00:22:11,664
All passengers
prepare for immediate boarding.

322
00:22:23,259 --> 00:22:24,635
Excuse me.

323
00:22:24,760 --> 00:22:28,472
-Hey, what was your name? Creet?
-That's right, miss.

324
00:22:28,597 --> 00:22:30,307
Who are you with, Creet? You got family?

325
00:22:30,432 --> 00:22:32,601
No, miss. There's just me.

326
00:22:33,644 --> 00:22:37,606
Well, good luck. What do you think
it's gonna be like in Utopia?

327
00:22:37,690 --> 00:22:41,485
My mum used to say
the skies were made of diamonds.

328
00:22:42,152 --> 00:22:45,239
Good for her.
Go on, off you go, get your seat.

329
00:22:55,207 --> 00:22:57,001
(SNARLING)

330
00:22:58,752 --> 00:23:01,672
-Is that...
-Gluten extract.

331
00:23:01,755 --> 00:23:04,508
It binds the neutralino map together.

332
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:06,427
But that's food.

333
00:23:06,510 --> 00:23:10,764
You've built this system out of food
and string and staples?

334
00:23:10,848 --> 00:23:14,894
-Professor Yana, you're a genius.
-Says the man who made it work.

335
00:23:14,977 --> 00:23:19,148
Oh, it's easy coming in at the end.
But you're stellar.

336
00:23:19,648 --> 00:23:23,861
This is magnificent.
And I don't often say that 'cause...

337
00:23:23,986 --> 00:23:25,905
Well, 'cause of me.

338
00:23:25,988 --> 00:23:28,908
Well, even my title is an affectation.

339
00:23:28,991 --> 00:23:33,787
There hasn't been such a thing
as a university for over 1,000 years.

340
00:23:33,871 --> 00:23:38,125
I've spent my life going
from one refugee ship to another.

341
00:23:38,208 --> 00:23:41,879
If you'd been born in a different time,
you'd be revered. I mean it.

342
00:23:42,004 --> 00:23:43,297
Throughout the galaxies.

343
00:23:43,380 --> 00:23:48,344
Oh, those damn galaxies,
they had to go and collapse.

344
00:23:48,510 --> 00:23:53,432
Some admiration would have been nice.
Yes, just a little. Just once.

345
00:23:53,515 --> 00:23:55,809
Well, you've got it now.

346
00:23:55,893 --> 00:23:58,437
But that Footprint engine thing...

347
00:23:59,855 --> 00:24:03,692
You can't activate it from on-board.
It's got to be done from here.

348
00:24:03,859 --> 00:24:05,277
You're staying behind.

349
00:24:05,361 --> 00:24:09,365
With Chantho. She won't leave
without me. Simply refuses.

350
00:24:09,782 --> 00:24:11,825
You'd give your life so they could fly.

351
00:24:11,909 --> 00:24:17,247
Oh, I think I'm a little too old
for Utopia. Time I had some sleep.

352
00:24:17,331 --> 00:24:20,626
Professor, tell the Doctor
we've found his blue box.

353
00:24:20,709 --> 00:24:22,878
-Ah.
-Doctor?

354
00:24:26,173 --> 00:24:29,093
Professor, it's a wild stab in the dark,

355
00:24:29,218 --> 00:24:32,096
but I might just have found you
a way out.

356
00:24:44,233 --> 00:24:45,693
Extra power.

357
00:24:47,444 --> 00:24:49,571
Little bit of a cheat,
but who's counting?

358
00:24:49,655 --> 00:24:52,157
Jack, you're in charge
of the retro feeds.

359
00:24:52,241 --> 00:24:54,076
Oh, am I glad to see that thing.

360
00:24:54,159 --> 00:24:56,829
Chan, Professor, are you all right, tho?

361
00:24:56,912 --> 00:24:59,873
Yeah, I'm fine, I'm fine.
I'm fine. Just get on with it.

362
00:24:59,957 --> 00:25:02,376
Connect those circuits into the spar,
same as the last lot.

363
00:25:02,459 --> 00:25:05,546
-But quicker.
-MARTHA: Yes, sir.

364
00:25:06,588 --> 00:25:08,674
You don't have to keep working.
We can handle it.

365
00:25:08,757 --> 00:25:13,137
It's just a headache,
just noise inside my head, Doctor.

366
00:25:13,262 --> 00:25:16,640
-Constant noise inside my head.
-What sort of noise?

367
00:25:17,433 --> 00:25:19,518
The sound of drums.

368
00:25:19,601 --> 00:25:22,646
More and more,
as though it's getting closer.

369
00:25:22,730 --> 00:25:25,899
-When did it start?
-I've had it all my life.

370
00:25:26,275 --> 00:25:28,819
Every waking hour.

371
00:25:28,902 --> 00:25:32,114
Still, no rest for the wicked.

372
00:25:34,033 --> 00:25:36,118
So how long have you been
with the Professor?

373
00:25:36,201 --> 00:25:38,579
Chan, 17 years, tho.

374
00:25:38,662 --> 00:25:42,082
-Blimey. Long time.
-Chan, I adore him, tho.

375
00:25:42,958 --> 00:25:44,585
Oh, right. And he...

376
00:25:44,668 --> 00:25:47,421
Chan, I don't think
he even notices, tho.

377
00:25:47,504 --> 00:25:51,842
-Tell me about it.
-Chan, but I am happy to serve, tho.

378
00:25:51,925 --> 00:25:55,345
Do you mind if I ask? Do you have
to start every sentence with "Chan"?

379
00:25:55,471 --> 00:25:58,974
-Chan, yes, tho.
-And end every sentence with...

380
00:25:59,058 --> 00:26:02,352
-Chan, tho, tho.
-What would happen if you didn't?

381
00:26:02,436 --> 00:26:04,813
Chan, that would be rude, tho.

382
00:26:06,940 --> 00:26:10,861
-What, like swearing?
-Chan, indeed, tho.

383
00:26:11,403 --> 00:26:15,157
-Go on. Just once.
-Chan, I can't, tho.

384
00:26:15,240 --> 00:26:18,827
-Do it for me.
-No.

385
00:26:18,911 --> 00:26:20,454
(GIGGLING)

386
00:26:24,166 --> 00:26:28,170
Professor. Systems are down.

387
00:26:30,172 --> 00:26:32,549
Professor, are you getting me?

388
00:26:32,633 --> 00:26:34,051
I'm here! We're ready.

389
00:26:34,718 --> 00:26:37,721
Now all you need to do
is connect the couplings,

390
00:26:37,846 --> 00:26:39,515
then we can launch.

391
00:26:39,598 --> 00:26:41,975
Save us, this equipment!

392
00:26:42,059 --> 00:26:44,645
-Needs rebooting all the time.
-Anything I can do?

393
00:26:44,728 --> 00:26:46,480
-I've finished that lot.
-Yes, if you could.

394
00:26:46,563 --> 00:26:49,775
Just press the reboot key
every time the picture goes.

395
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:52,528
Certainly, sir.
Just don't ask me to do shorthand.

396
00:26:53,695 --> 00:26:56,073
-Are you still there?
-Present and correct.

397
00:26:56,156 --> 00:26:59,409
Send your man inside.
We'll keep the levels down from here.

398
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:12,548
He's inside.

399
00:27:12,923 --> 00:27:15,676
Captain, keep the dials below the red.

400
00:27:15,759 --> 00:27:18,220
-Where is that room?
-It's underneath the rocket.

401
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:20,722
Fix the couplings
and the Footprint can work.

402
00:27:20,806 --> 00:27:24,768
But the entire chamber
is flooded with stet radiation.

403
00:27:24,852 --> 00:27:26,228
Stet? Never heard of it.

404
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:28,188
You wouldn't want to.
But it's safe enough

405
00:27:28,272 --> 00:27:30,691
if we can hold the radiation
back from here.

406
00:27:54,798 --> 00:27:56,091
(ALARM BEEPING)

407
00:27:56,175 --> 00:27:58,260
It's rising. 0.2.

408
00:27:58,385 --> 00:28:00,262
-Keep it level.
-Yes, sir.

409
00:28:18,864 --> 00:28:21,241
(ALARM BUZZING)

410
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:25,871
We're losing power, tho.

411
00:28:43,764 --> 00:28:46,516
-DOCTOR: Radiation's rising.
-We've lost control!

412
00:28:46,642 --> 00:28:50,646
-The chamber's going to flood!
-Jack! Override the vents!

413
00:28:53,148 --> 00:28:57,152
Get out! Get out of there!

414
00:28:57,861 --> 00:28:59,196
Jate!

415
00:28:59,363 --> 00:29:00,906
GUARD: Hey, you!

416
00:29:03,158 --> 00:29:04,243
Stop!

417
00:29:04,326 --> 00:29:05,494
(MACHINE GUNS FIRING)

418
00:29:07,704 --> 00:29:10,749
-We can jump-start the override.
-Don't. It's gonna flare!

419
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:12,876
(SCREAMING)

420
00:29:19,174 --> 00:29:21,760
Jate, get out of there! Get out!

421
00:29:27,724 --> 00:29:29,268
No!

422
00:29:29,685 --> 00:29:33,063
-I've got him.
-Chan, don't touch the cables, tho.

423
00:29:34,898 --> 00:29:36,733
I'm so sorry.

424
00:29:36,817 --> 00:29:39,069
The chamber's flooded
with radiation, yes?

425
00:29:39,152 --> 00:29:42,072
Without the couplings,
the engines will never start.

426
00:29:42,155 --> 00:29:44,741
-It was all for nothing.
-Oh, I don't know.

427
00:29:46,493 --> 00:29:50,789
-Martha, leave him.
-You've got to let me try.

428
00:29:50,872 --> 00:29:53,959
Come on, come on, just listen to me.
Now leave him alone.

429
00:29:54,042 --> 00:29:57,963
Strikes me, Professor, you've got a room
which no man can enter without dying.

430
00:29:58,046 --> 00:30:00,132
-Is that correct?
-Yes.

431
00:30:00,215 --> 00:30:01,300
Well...

432
00:30:01,383 --> 00:30:03,010
(GASPING)

433
00:30:04,386 --> 00:30:07,097
I think I've got just the man.

434
00:30:07,264 --> 00:30:09,599
Was someone kissing me?

435
00:30:16,273 --> 00:30:18,817
Lieutenant, get on-board the rocket.
I promise you're going to fly.

436
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:20,652
-The chamber's flooded.
-Trust me, we found a way

437
00:30:20,736 --> 00:30:22,904
of tripping the system. Run!

438
00:30:24,281 --> 00:30:26,283
What are you taking
your clothes off for?

439
00:30:26,366 --> 00:30:27,868
-I'm going in.
-By the looks of it,

440
00:30:27,951 --> 00:30:30,454
I'd say that stet radiation
doesn't affect clothing, only flesh.

441
00:30:30,537 --> 00:30:32,664
Well, I look good, though.

442
00:30:34,875 --> 00:30:36,877
How long have you known?

443
00:30:37,753 --> 00:30:40,130
Ever since I ran away from you.

444
00:30:40,797 --> 00:30:42,215
Good luck.

445
00:30:56,563 --> 00:30:58,940
MARTHA: We lost picture
when that thing flared up.

446
00:30:59,024 --> 00:31:00,400
Doctor, are you there?

447
00:31:00,484 --> 00:31:03,278
Receiving, yeah. He's inside.

448
00:31:03,653 --> 00:31:05,530
-And still alive?
-Oh, yes.

449
00:31:05,614 --> 00:31:09,117
But he should evaporate.
What sort of a man is he?

450
00:31:09,201 --> 00:31:10,911
I've only just met him.

451
00:31:10,994 --> 00:31:15,499
The Doctor sort of travels through time
and space and picks people up.

452
00:31:15,624 --> 00:31:20,003
God, I make us sound like stray dogs.
Maybe we are.

453
00:31:20,087 --> 00:31:24,633
-He travels in time?
-Don't ask me to explain it.

454
00:31:24,716 --> 00:31:28,637
That's a Tardis, that box thing.
The sports car of time travel, he says.

455
00:31:30,597 --> 00:31:32,682
(DRUMS BEATING)

456
00:31:32,808 --> 00:31:36,228
VOICE: Inside the box, inside the box...

457
00:31:38,021 --> 00:31:39,815
When did you realise?

458
00:31:39,981 --> 00:31:41,817
Earth, 1892.

459
00:31:42,275 --> 00:31:45,904
Got in a fight on Ellis Island,
a man shot me through the heart.

460
00:31:45,987 --> 00:31:49,408
And then I woke up.
Thought it was kind of strange.

461
00:31:49,908 --> 00:31:53,870
But then it never stopped.
Fell off a cliff, trampled by horses,

462
00:31:53,995 --> 00:31:58,083
World War I, World War II.
Poison, starvation, a stray javelin.

463
00:31:58,208 --> 00:31:59,376
Ooh!

464
00:31:59,501 --> 00:32:05,215
In the end, I got the message.
I'm the man who can never die.

465
00:32:06,883 --> 00:32:10,720
-And all that time you knew.
-That's why I left you behind.

466
00:32:10,804 --> 00:32:15,267
It's not easy,
even just looking at you, Jack,

467
00:32:15,350 --> 00:32:17,936
-'cause you're wrong.
-Thanks.

468
00:32:18,019 --> 00:32:20,021
You are. I can't help it.

469
00:32:20,105 --> 00:32:23,358
I'm a Time Lord.
It's instinct. It's in my guts.

470
00:32:25,277 --> 00:32:28,864
You're a fixed point in time and space.
You're a fact.

471
00:32:29,698 --> 00:32:31,324
That's never meant to happen.

472
00:32:31,408 --> 00:32:35,078
Even the Tardis reacted against you,
tried to shake you off.

473
00:32:35,162 --> 00:32:37,622
Flew all the way to the end
of the universe just to get rid of you.

474
00:32:37,706 --> 00:32:42,419
So what you're saying is
you're prejudiced?

475
00:32:43,962 --> 00:32:45,839
I never thought of it like that.

476
00:32:45,922 --> 00:32:48,425
-Shame on you.
-Yeah.

477
00:32:48,550 --> 00:32:52,304
JACK: Last thing I remember,
back when I was mortal,

478
00:32:52,387 --> 00:32:55,640
I was facing three Daleks,
death by extermination.

479
00:32:55,724 --> 00:32:58,894
VOICE: Daleks... Daleks...
JACK: Then I came back to life.

480
00:33:00,395 --> 00:33:02,522
-What happened?
-Rose.

481
00:33:03,398 --> 00:33:05,108
JACK: I thought
you'd sent her back home.

482
00:33:05,192 --> 00:33:06,735
DOCTOR: She came back.

483
00:33:06,818 --> 00:33:10,113
Opened the heart of the Tardis
and absorbed the time vortex itself.

484
00:33:10,197 --> 00:33:11,573
JACK: What does that mean exactly?

485
00:33:11,656 --> 00:33:13,909
DOCTOR: No one's ever meant
to have that power.

486
00:33:13,992 --> 00:33:17,829
If a Time Lord did that,
he'd become a god, a vengeful god.

487
00:33:18,205 --> 00:33:19,706
But she was human.

488
00:33:21,082 --> 00:33:22,584
I bring life.

489
00:33:25,545 --> 00:33:28,381
Everything she did was so human.

490
00:33:29,007 --> 00:33:31,009
She brought you back to life.

491
00:33:31,384 --> 00:33:34,763
But she couldn't control it.
She brought you back forever.

492
00:33:34,888 --> 00:33:39,935
That's something, I suppose.
The final act of the Time War was life.

493
00:33:41,603 --> 00:33:43,647
JACK: Do you think
she could change me back?

494
00:33:43,772 --> 00:33:46,441
DOCTOR: I took the power out of her.

495
00:33:47,943 --> 00:33:50,195
She's gone, Jack.

496
00:33:50,612 --> 00:33:54,241
She's not just living on
a parallel world, she's trapped there.

497
00:33:56,201 --> 00:33:58,620
The walls have closed.

498
00:33:58,703 --> 00:34:01,248
-I'm sorry.
-Yeah.

499
00:34:01,331 --> 00:34:06,461
I went back to her estate
in the '90s, just once or twice.

500
00:34:08,255 --> 00:34:10,215
Watched her growing up.

501
00:34:10,799 --> 00:34:14,177
Never said hello,
timelines and all that.

502
00:34:15,637 --> 00:34:19,349
-Do you want to die?
-This one's a little stuck.

503
00:34:20,308 --> 00:34:21,810
Jack?

504
00:34:23,853 --> 00:34:26,439
I thought I did. I don't know.

505
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:35,198
But this lot, you see them out here
surviving and that's fantastic.

506
00:34:39,202 --> 00:34:43,290
-You might be out there somewhere.
-I could go meet myself.

507
00:34:43,373 --> 00:34:47,377
Well, it's the only man
you're ever gonna be happy with.

508
00:34:48,336 --> 00:34:51,673
This new regeneration,
it's kinda cheeky.

509
00:34:53,341 --> 00:34:55,802
VOICE: Regeneration. Regeneration.

510
00:34:55,885 --> 00:34:58,847
I never understand
half the things he's saying.

511
00:34:59,639 --> 00:35:03,435
-What's wrong?
-Chan, Professor, what is it, tho?

512
00:35:03,518 --> 00:35:05,812
Time travel.

513
00:35:06,187 --> 00:35:10,650
They say there was time travel
back in the old days.

514
00:35:11,443 --> 00:35:13,570
I never believed.

515
00:35:14,821 --> 00:35:18,700
But what would I know? Stupid old man.

516
00:35:20,201 --> 00:35:25,165
Never could keep time.
Always late, always lost.

517
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:30,003
Even this thing never worked.

518
00:35:30,962 --> 00:35:35,759
Martha, this watch is me.
I'm gonna become human.

519
00:35:37,052 --> 00:35:42,641
Time and time and time again,
always running out on me.

520
00:35:43,350 --> 00:35:49,230
-Can I have a look at that?
-It's only an old relic. Like me!

521
00:35:50,440 --> 00:35:52,525
-Where did you get it?
-Hmm?

522
00:35:53,902 --> 00:35:56,905
-I was found with it.
-What do you mean?

523
00:35:56,988 --> 00:35:59,199
An orphan in the storm.

524
00:35:59,282 --> 00:36:05,038
I was a naked child found
on the coast of the Silver Devastation.

525
00:36:05,580 --> 00:36:08,416
Abandoned. With only this.

526
00:36:08,500 --> 00:36:11,211
-Have you ever opened it?
-Why would I? It's broken.

527
00:36:11,419 --> 00:36:14,464
How do you know it's broken
if you've never opened it?

528
00:36:14,589 --> 00:36:19,427
It's stuck, it's old,
it's not meant to be.

529
00:36:21,096 --> 00:36:22,555
I don't know.

530
00:36:30,188 --> 00:36:31,773
Does it matter?

531
00:36:32,691 --> 00:36:36,653
No, it's nothing. It's...

532
00:36:37,946 --> 00:36:42,534
Listen, everything's fine up here.
I'm gonna see if the Doctor needs me.

533
00:36:44,828 --> 00:36:47,622
-Yes!
-Now, get out of there, come on!

534
00:36:54,129 --> 00:36:56,923
-Lieutenant, everyone on board?
-Ready and waiting.

535
00:36:57,006 --> 00:36:59,801
Stand by! Two minutes to ignition.

536
00:36:59,884 --> 00:37:02,387
ATILLO: Ready to launch.

537
00:37:02,470 --> 00:37:08,852
Outer doors sealed.
Launching in T minus 99, 98...

538
00:37:12,647 --> 00:37:14,649
Ah, nearly there.
The Footprint, it's a gravity pulse.

539
00:37:14,816 --> 00:37:16,401
It stamps down, the rocket shoots up.

540
00:37:16,484 --> 00:37:18,653
Bit primitive. Gonna take
the both of us to keep it stable.

541
00:37:18,778 --> 00:37:20,613
(BEEPING)

542
00:37:20,697 --> 00:37:24,701
Doctor, it's the Professor. He's got
this watch, he's got a fob watch.

543
00:37:24,826 --> 00:37:27,871
It's the same as yours,
same writing on it, same everything.

544
00:37:27,996 --> 00:37:30,081
-Don't be ridiculous.
-I asked him.

545
00:37:30,165 --> 00:37:33,460
-He said he's had it his whole life.
-So he's got the same watch.

546
00:37:33,543 --> 00:37:36,254
Yeah, but it's not a watch.
It's this chameleon thing.

547
00:37:36,337 --> 00:37:40,592
No, no, no, it's this thing...
This device, it rewrites biology.

548
00:37:40,675 --> 00:37:42,969
Changes a Time Lord into a human.

549
00:37:43,052 --> 00:37:45,847
-And it's the same watch!
-It can't be.

550
00:37:47,348 --> 00:37:48,767
That means he could be a Time Lord.

551
00:37:48,850 --> 00:37:51,186
-You might not be the last one!
-Jack, keep it level!

552
00:37:51,269 --> 00:37:54,314
-But that's brilliant, isn't it?
-Yes, it is. Of course it is.

553
00:37:54,397 --> 00:37:58,151
Depends which one. Brilliant, fantastic,
yeah. But they died, the Time Lords.

554
00:37:58,234 --> 00:38:00,779
-All of them, they died.
-Not if he was human.

555
00:38:00,862 --> 00:38:04,157
What did he say, Martha?
What did he say?

556
00:38:05,533 --> 00:38:08,119
He looked at the watch
like he could hardly see it.

557
00:38:08,203 --> 00:38:09,871
Like that perception filter thing.

558
00:38:09,954 --> 00:38:12,874
What about now? Can he see it now?

559
00:38:14,042 --> 00:38:16,669
DOCTOR: The Tardis. The time vortex.

560
00:38:18,630 --> 00:38:20,715
VOICE: Regeneration.

561
00:38:22,383 --> 00:38:25,804
It's the drums, the drums, the drums,
the never-ending drumbeat.

562
00:38:25,887 --> 00:38:30,725
Open me, you human fool. Open the light
and summon me and receive my majesty.

563
00:38:31,684 --> 00:38:36,022
Destroy him.
Then you will give your power to me.

564
00:38:37,732 --> 00:38:41,820
Chan, Yana, won't you please
take some rest, tho?

565
00:38:44,948 --> 00:38:47,325
ATILLO: 77, 70, 9...

566
00:38:47,408 --> 00:38:49,369
If he escaped the Time War,
then it's a perfect place to hide.

567
00:38:49,452 --> 00:38:50,995
The end of the universe.

568
00:38:51,079 --> 00:38:54,958
Think what the Face of Boe said.
His dying words.

569
00:38:55,083 --> 00:38:56,626
He said...

570
00:38:59,045 --> 00:39:01,089
(RUMBLING)

571
00:39:15,436 --> 00:39:16,938
You

572
00:39:17,105 --> 00:39:18,523
are

573
00:39:18,606 --> 00:39:19,983
not

574
00:39:20,066 --> 00:39:21,401
alone.

575
00:39:37,292 --> 00:39:40,086
Chan, Professor Yana, tho?

576
00:39:53,099 --> 00:39:55,602
Lieutenant, have you done it?
Did you get velocity?

577
00:39:56,185 --> 00:39:59,522
Have you done it?
Lieutenant, have you done it?

578
00:39:59,606 --> 00:40:02,191
ATILLO: Affirmative.
We'll see you in Utopia.

579
00:40:02,275 --> 00:40:03,985
Good luck.

580
00:40:09,532 --> 00:40:12,744
-Chan, but you've locked them in, tho.
-Door open.

581
00:40:12,827 --> 00:40:14,329
Door open!

582
00:40:14,787 --> 00:40:18,666
Not to worry, my dear.
As one door closes, another must open.

583
00:40:22,962 --> 00:40:24,672
(SNARLING)

584
00:40:26,215 --> 00:40:28,301
Chan, you must stop, tho.

585
00:40:34,015 --> 00:40:38,186
Chan, but you've lowered the defences.
The Futurekind will get in, tho.

586
00:40:47,528 --> 00:40:51,741
Chan, Professor, I'm so sorry,

587
00:40:53,284 --> 00:40:55,954
but I must stop you.

588
00:40:56,037 --> 00:40:58,456
You are destroying all our work, tho.

589
00:40:59,540 --> 00:41:06,255
Oh! Now I can say I was provoked.

590
00:41:16,516 --> 00:41:20,853
Did you never think,
all those years standing beside me,

591
00:41:20,937 --> 00:41:24,273
to ask about that watch? Never?

592
00:41:25,233 --> 00:41:31,114
Did you never once think, not ever,
that you could set me free?

593
00:41:31,197 --> 00:41:33,616
Chan, I'm sorry, tho.

594
00:41:33,908 --> 00:41:36,327
Chan, I'm so sorry.

595
00:41:36,411 --> 00:41:40,373
And you, with your
"Chan" and your "tho",

596
00:41:40,456 --> 00:41:43,334
driving me insane.

597
00:41:43,418 --> 00:41:46,921
-Chan, Professor, please.
-That is not my name!

598
00:41:48,297 --> 00:41:52,093
The professor was an invention.

599
00:41:53,428 --> 00:41:57,932
So perfect a disguise
that I forgot who I am.

600
00:41:58,016 --> 00:42:01,352
Chan, then who are you, tho?

601
00:42:01,811 --> 00:42:04,397
I am

602
00:42:05,940 --> 00:42:08,276
the Master.

603
00:42:14,574 --> 00:42:15,992
This way!

604
00:42:27,628 --> 00:42:29,130
Professor!

605
00:42:30,423 --> 00:42:33,426
Professor, let me in! Let me in!

606
00:42:34,469 --> 00:42:36,345
Jack, get the door open, now!

607
00:42:36,429 --> 00:42:38,973
Professor, Professor, where are you?

608
00:42:39,098 --> 00:42:40,767
Chantho, Chantho, are you there?

609
00:42:40,850 --> 00:42:45,104
Please, I need to explain.
Whatever you do, don't open that watch.

610
00:42:45,188 --> 00:42:46,773
Utopia.

611
00:42:47,315 --> 00:42:48,816
Hurry!

612
00:42:52,111 --> 00:42:55,656
Open the door! Open the door, please.

613
00:42:57,658 --> 00:43:00,870
I am begging you, Professor.
Please listen to me.

614
00:43:00,995 --> 00:43:02,997
Just open the door, please.

615
00:43:37,073 --> 00:43:38,616
And locked.

616
00:43:38,699 --> 00:43:41,035
Let me in. Let me in!

617
00:43:41,828 --> 00:43:44,372
-She's dead.
-I broke the lock. Give me a hand.

618
00:43:44,539 --> 00:43:46,165
I'm begging you. Everything's changed.

619
00:43:46,249 --> 00:43:49,752
It's only the two of us.
We're the only ones left.

620
00:43:50,378 --> 00:43:51,504
Just let me in!

621
00:43:52,797 --> 00:43:55,049
Killed by an insect.

622
00:43:55,925 --> 00:43:57,552
A girl.

623
00:43:58,177 --> 00:44:00,263
How inappropriate.

624
00:44:01,013 --> 00:44:06,853
But still, if the Doctor
can be young and strong,

625
00:44:08,521 --> 00:44:10,565
then so can I.

626
00:44:14,193 --> 00:44:16,737
The Master,

627
00:44:17,989 --> 00:44:20,700
reborn.

628
00:44:42,763 --> 00:44:43,973
(SCREAMING)

629
00:44:44,098 --> 00:44:46,267
Doctor, you'd better think of something!

630
00:45:06,245 --> 00:45:09,373
(LAUGHING)

631
00:45:13,336 --> 00:45:15,463
Now then, Doctor.

632
00:45:16,088 --> 00:45:17,632
Oh, new voice.

633
00:45:17,715 --> 00:45:19,342
Hello. Hello.

634
00:45:20,009 --> 00:45:21,427
Hello.

635
00:45:21,510 --> 00:45:25,306
Anyway, why don't we stop
and have a nice little chat

636
00:45:25,431 --> 00:45:28,309
while I tell you all my plans
and you can work out a way to stop me?

637
00:45:28,434 --> 00:45:29,852
I don't think!

638
00:45:29,936 --> 00:45:32,146
Hold on, I know that voice.

639
00:45:32,813 --> 00:45:34,273
(SCREAMING)

640
00:45:34,357 --> 00:45:37,860
I'm asking you, really properly,
just stop, just think.

641
00:45:37,944 --> 00:45:40,863
-Use my name.
-Master.

642
00:45:43,241 --> 00:45:45,868
-I'm sorry.
-Tough!

643
00:45:50,623 --> 00:45:52,959
JACK: I can't hold them
much longer, Doctor!

644
00:45:57,505 --> 00:45:59,173
No, you don't.

645
00:46:02,677 --> 00:46:06,138
End of the universe. Have fun. Bye-bye.

646
00:46:06,597 --> 00:46:08,266
Doctor, stop him!

647
00:46:09,517 --> 00:46:11,269
(WHOOSHING)

648
00:46:12,395 --> 00:46:14,438
Hurry up, they're getting in!

649
00:47:16,042 --> 00:47:18,502
Let the work of Government begin.

650
00:47:18,586 --> 00:47:21,881
Diplomatic relations with a new species.

651
00:47:21,964 --> 00:47:23,758
And these are my friends.

652
00:47:27,720 --> 00:47:30,306
-Take aim. Fire!
-Run for your life.

653
00:47:31,349 --> 00:47:32,808
I said run!

654
00:47:32,892 --> 00:47:35,686
REPORTER: Air Force One
has landed on British soil.

655
00:47:35,770 --> 00:47:37,063
Mr President, sir!

656
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:39,231
From now on,
UNIT has control of this operation.

657
00:47:39,315 --> 00:47:43,569
And what this country
really needs right now

658
00:47:43,694 --> 00:47:45,446
ls a Doctor.

